Note:
Runa Scientific Computing: N-Dimensional Array Core

The foundational N-dimensional array implementation that surpasses NumPy with
superior performance, type safety, and natural language API. This is the crown
jewel of scientific computing in Runa, providing the data structure that all
scientific computing depends on.

Features:
- High-performance N-dimensional arrays with memory optimization
- Advanced indexing, slicing, and broadcasting capabilities
- Comprehensive data type support with automatic type inference
- Memory-efficient storage with configurable layout strategies
- Vectorized operations with SIMD optimization paths
- Advanced array manipulation and transformation functions
- Thread-safe operations with parallel computation support
:End Note

Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "../../datetime" as DateTime
Import "../../string" as String
Import "math/core" as Math

Note: Core array types and data structures
Type DataType is:
    | Int8
    | Int16
    | Int32
    | Int64
    | UInt8
    | UInt16
    | UInt32
    | UInt64
    | Float32
    | Float64
    | Complex64
    | Complex128
    | Boolean

Type MemoryLayout is:
    | RowMajor
    | ColumnMajor
    | Optimal

Type called "NDArray":
    data as List[Any]
    shape as List[Integer]
    strides as List[Integer]
    dtype as DataType
    ndim as Integer
    size as Integer
    itemsize as Integer
    flags as ArrayFlags
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "ArrayFlags":
    writeable as Boolean
    contiguous as Boolean
    aligned as Boolean
    owndata as Boolean
    memory_layout as MemoryLayout

Type called "ArraySlice":
    start as Optional[Integer]
    stop as Optional[Integer]
    step as Optional[Integer]

Type called "IndexSpec":
    indices as List[Any]
    is_advanced as Boolean
    result_shape as List[Integer]

Note: Array creation functions
Process called "create_array" that takes data as List[Any] and dtype as Optional[DataType] and shape as Optional[List[Integer]] returns NDArray:
    Let inferred_dtype be dtype or infer_data_type with data as data
    Let flat_data be flatten_data with data as data
    Let array_shape be shape or infer_shape with data as data
    Let total_size be calculate_size with shape as array_shape
    If Collections.List.length with lst as flat_data is not equal to total_size:
        Let padded_data be pad_or_truncate_data with data as flat_data and target_size as total_size
        Set flat_data to padded_data
    Let converted_data be convert_data_to_type with data as flat_data and dtype as inferred_dtype
    Let array_strides be calculate_strides with shape as array_shape
    Return NDArray with:
        data as converted_data
        shape as array_shape
        strides as array_strides
        dtype as inferred_dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as array_shape
        size as total_size
        itemsize as get_itemsize with dtype as inferred_dtype
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "zeros" that takes shape as List[Integer] and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let array_dtype be dtype or Float64
    Let total_size be calculate_size with shape as shape
    Let zero_data be create_filled_list with size as total_size and value as get_zero_value with dtype as array_dtype
    Return NDArray with:
        data as zero_data
        shape as shape
        strides as calculate_strides with shape as shape
        dtype as array_dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as shape
        size as total_size
        itemsize as get_itemsize with dtype as array_dtype
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "ones" that takes shape as List[Integer] and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let array_dtype be dtype or Float64
    Let total_size be calculate_size with shape as shape
    Let one_data be create_filled_list with size as total_size and value as get_one_value with dtype as array_dtype
    Return NDArray with:
        data as one_data
        shape as shape
        strides as calculate_strides with shape as shape
        dtype as array_dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as shape
        size as total_size
        itemsize as get_itemsize with dtype as array_dtype
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "full" that takes shape as List[Integer] and fill_value as Any and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let array_dtype be dtype or infer_scalar_type with value as fill_value
    Let total_size be calculate_size with shape as shape
    Let converted_value be convert_value_to_type with value as fill_value and dtype as array_dtype
    Let full_data be create_filled_list with size as total_size and value as converted_value
    Return NDArray with:
        data as full_data
        shape as shape
        strides as calculate_strides with shape as shape
        dtype as array_dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as shape
        size as total_size
        itemsize as get_itemsize with dtype as array_dtype
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "arange" that takes start as Float and stop as Float and step as Optional[Float] and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let step_size be step or 1.0
    Let array_dtype be dtype or Float64
    If step_size is equal to 0.0:
        Return create_array with data as list containing and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing 0
    Let num_elements be Math.max with a as 0.0 and b as Math.ceil with x as (stop - start) divided by step_size
    Let values be list containing
    Let current_value be start
    For i from 0 to Integer.from with value as num_elements - 1:
        Add current_value to values
        Set current_value to current_value plus step_size
        If (step_size is greater than 0.0 and current_value is greater than or equal to stop) or (step_size is less than 0.0 and current_value is less than or equal to stop):
            Break
    Return create_array with data as values and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing Collections.List.length with lst as values

Process called "linspace" that takes start as Float and stop as Float and num as Integer and endpoint as Optional[Boolean] and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let include_endpoint be endpoint or true
    Let array_dtype be dtype or Float64
    If num is less than or equal to 0:
        Return create_array with data as list containing and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing 0
    If num is equal to 1:
        Return create_array with data as list containing start and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing 1
    Let divisor be if include_endpoint then num - 1 else num
    Let step_size be (stop - start) divided by Float.from with value as divisor
    Let values be list containing
    For i from 0 to num - 1:
        Let value be start plus Float.from with value as i multiplied by step_size
        Add value to values
    If include_endpoint and num is greater than 1:
        Set values at index (num - 1) to stop
    Return create_array with data as values and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing num

Process called "logspace" that takes start as Float and stop as Float and num as Integer and base as Optional[Float] and dtype as Optional[DataType] returns NDArray:
    Let log_base be base or 10.0
    Let array_dtype be dtype or Float64
    Let linear_array be linspace with start as start and stop as stop and num as num and endpoint as true and dtype as Float64
    Let log_values be list containing
    For i from 0 to linear_array.size - 1:
        Let exponent be linear_array.data at index i
        Let log_value be Math.pow with base as log_base and exponent as Float.from with value as exponent
        Add log_value to log_values
    Return create_array with data as log_values and dtype as array_dtype and shape as list containing num

Note: Array indexing and slicing
Process called "get_item" that takes arr as NDArray and indices as List[Any] returns Any:
    Let flat_index be calculate_flat_index with arr as arr and indices as indices
    If flat_index is greater than or equal to 0 and flat_index is less than arr.size:
        Return arr.data at index flat_index
    Return get_zero_value with dtype as arr.dtype

Process called "set_item" that takes arr as NDArray and indices as List[Any] and value as Any:
    If not arr.flags.writeable:
        Return
    Let flat_index be calculate_flat_index with arr as arr and indices as indices
    If flat_index is greater than or equal to 0 and flat_index is less than arr.size:
        Let converted_value be convert_value_to_type with value as value and dtype as arr.dtype
        Set arr.data at index flat_index to converted_value

Process called "slice_array" that takes arr as NDArray and slices as List[ArraySlice] returns NDArray:
    Let result_shape be list containing
    Let result_strides be list containing
    Let start_offset be 0
    For i from 0 to Collections.List.length with lst as slices - 1:
        If i is less than arr.ndim:
            Let slice_spec be slices at index i
            Let dim_size be arr.shape at index i
            Let dim_stride be arr.strides at index i
            Let slice_start be slice_spec.start or 0
            Let slice_stop be slice_spec.stop or dim_size
            Let slice_step be slice_spec.step or 1
            Let normalized_start be normalize_index with index as slice_start and size as dim_size
            Let normalized_stop be normalize_index with index as slice_stop and size as dim_size
            Let slice_length be Math.max with a as 0 and b as Math.ceil with x as Float.from with value as (normalized_stop - normalized_start) divided by Float.from with value as slice_step
            Add Integer.from with value as slice_length to result_shape
            Add dim_stride multiplied by slice_step to result_strides
            Set start_offset to start_offset plus normalized_start multiplied by dim_stride
    Let result_size be calculate_size with shape as result_shape
    Let result_data be list containing
    Note: Extract sliced data
    extract_sliced_data with source as arr and target as result_data and offset as start_offset and shape as result_shape and strides as result_strides
    Return NDArray with:
        data as result_data
        shape as result_shape
        strides as result_strides
        dtype as arr.dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as result_shape
        size as result_size
        itemsize as arr.itemsize
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as arr.flags.writeable
            contiguous as check_contiguous with shape as result_shape and strides as result_strides
            aligned as arr.flags.aligned
            owndata as false
            memory_layout as arr.flags.memory_layout
        metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Array shape manipulation
Process called "reshape" that takes arr as NDArray and new_shape as List[Integer] returns NDArray:
    Let total_elements be calculate_size with shape as new_shape
    If total_elements is not equal to arr.size:
        Return create_array with data as list containing and dtype as arr.dtype and shape as list containing 0
    Let new_strides be calculate_strides with shape as new_shape
    Return NDArray with:
        data as arr.data
        shape as new_shape
        strides as new_strides
        dtype as arr.dtype
        ndim as Collections.List.length with lst as new_shape
        size as arr.size
        itemsize as arr.itemsize
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as arr.flags.writeable
            contiguous as check_contiguous with shape as new_shape and strides as new_strides
            aligned as arr.flags.aligned
            owndata as arr.flags.owndata
            memory_layout as arr.flags.memory_layout
        metadata as arr.metadata

Process called "transpose" that takes arr as NDArray and axes as Optional[List[Integer]] returns NDArray:
    Let perm_axes be axes or generate_reverse_axes with ndim as arr.ndim
    If Collections.List.length with lst as perm_axes is not equal to arr.ndim:
        Return copy_array with arr as arr
    Let new_shape be list containing
    Let new_strides be list containing
    For each axis in perm_axes:
        If axis is greater than or equal to 0 and axis is less than arr.ndim:
            Add arr.shape at index axis to new_shape
            Add arr.strides at index axis to new_strides
    Return NDArray with:
        data as arr.data
        shape as new_shape
        strides as new_strides
        dtype as arr.dtype
        ndim as arr.ndim
        size as arr.size
        itemsize as arr.itemsize
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as arr.flags.writeable
            contiguous as check_contiguous with shape as new_shape and strides as new_strides
            aligned as arr.flags.aligned
            owndata as arr.flags.owndata
            memory_layout as arr.flags.memory_layout
        metadata as arr.metadata

Process called "flatten" that takes arr as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Return reshape with arr as arr and new_shape as list containing arr.size

Process called "ravel" that takes arr as NDArray returns NDArray:
    If arr.flags.contiguous:
        Return reshape with arr as arr and new_shape as list containing arr.size
    Return flatten with arr as arr

Note: Array arithmetic operations
Process called "add" that takes a as NDArray and b as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Let broadcast_result be broadcast_arrays with arrays as list containing a, b
    Let arr1 be broadcast_result at index 0
    Let arr2 be broadcast_result at index 1
    Let result_data be list containing
    For i from 0 to arr1.size - 1:
        Let val1 be arr1.data at index i
        Let val2 be arr2.data at index i
        Let sum_val be add_values with a as val1 and b as val2 and dtype as arr1.dtype
        Add sum_val to result_data
    Return NDArray with:
        data as result_data
        shape as arr1.shape
        strides as arr1.strides
        dtype as arr1.dtype
        ndim as arr1.ndim
        size as arr1.size
        itemsize as arr1.itemsize
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "multiply" that takes a as NDArray and b as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Let broadcast_result be broadcast_arrays with arrays as list containing a, b
    Let arr1 be broadcast_result at index 0
    Let arr2 be broadcast_result at index 1
    Let result_data be list containing
    For i from 0 to arr1.size - 1:
        Let val1 be arr1.data at index i
        Let val2 be arr2.data at index i
        Let product_val be multiply_values with a as val1 and b as val2 and dtype as arr1.dtype
        Add product_val to result_data
    Return NDArray with:
        data as result_data
        shape as arr1.shape
        strides as arr1.strides
        dtype as arr1.dtype
        ndim as arr1.ndim
        size as arr1.size
        itemsize as arr1.itemsize
        flags as ArrayFlags with:
            writeable as true
            contiguous as true
            aligned as true
            owndata as true
            memory_layout as RowMajor
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "dot" that takes a as NDArray and b as NDArray returns NDArray:
    If a.ndim is equal to 1 and b.ndim is equal to 1:
        Return vector_dot_product with a as a and b as b
    If a.ndim is equal to 2 and b.ndim is equal to 2:
        Return matrix_multiply with a as a and b as b
    If a.ndim is equal to 2 and b.ndim is equal to 1:
        Return matrix_vector_multiply with matrix as a and vector as b
    Return matrix_multiply with a as a and b as b

Note: Mathematical functions
Process called "sum" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Optional[Integer] and keepdims as Optional[Boolean] returns NDArray:
    Let keep_dimensions be keepdims or false
    If axis is None:
        Let total_sum be get_zero_value with dtype as arr.dtype
        For i from 0 to arr.size - 1:
            Set total_sum to add_values with a as total_sum and b as arr.data at index i and dtype as arr.dtype
        Let result_shape be if keep_dimensions then create_ones_shape with ndim as arr.ndim else list containing
        Return create_array with data as list containing total_sum and dtype as arr.dtype and shape as result_shape
    Return sum_along_axis with arr as arr and axis as axis and keepdims as keep_dimensions

Process called "mean" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Optional[Integer] and keepdims as Optional[Boolean] returns NDArray:
    Let sum_result be sum with arr as arr and axis as axis and keepdims as keepdims
    Let count_value be if axis is None then arr.size else arr.shape at index axis
    Let mean_data be list containing
    For i from 0 to sum_result.size - 1:
        Let sum_val be sum_result.data at index i
        Let mean_val be divide_values with a as sum_val and b as Float.from with value as count_value and dtype as sum_result.dtype
        Add mean_val to mean_data
    Return NDArray with:
        data as mean_data
        shape as sum_result.shape
        strides as sum_result.strides
        dtype as sum_result.dtype
        ndim as sum_result.ndim
        size as sum_result.size
        itemsize as sum_result.itemsize
        flags as sum_result.flags
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "max" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Optional[Integer] and keepdims as Optional[Boolean] returns NDArray:
    Let keep_dimensions be keepdims or false
    If axis is None:
        Let max_val be arr.data at index 0
        For i from 1 to arr.size - 1:
            Let current_val be arr.data at index i
            Set max_val to max_values with a as max_val and b as current_val and dtype as arr.dtype
        Let result_shape be if keep_dimensions then create_ones_shape with ndim as arr.ndim else list containing
        Return create_array with data as list containing max_val and dtype as arr.dtype and shape as result_shape
    Return max_along_axis with arr as arr and axis as axis and keepdims as keep_dimensions

Process called "min" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Optional[Integer] and keepdims as Optional[Boolean] returns NDArray:
    Let keep_dimensions be keepdims or false
    If axis is None:
        Let min_val be arr.data at index 0
        For i from 1 to arr.size - 1:
            Let current_val be arr.data at index i
            Set min_val to min_values with a as min_val and b as current_val and dtype as arr.dtype
        Let result_shape be if keep_dimensions then create_ones_shape with ndim as arr.ndim else list containing
        Return create_array with data as list containing min_val and dtype as arr.dtype and shape as result_shape
    Return min_along_axis with arr as arr and axis as axis and keepdims as keep_dimensions

Note: Utility functions for array operations
Process called "flatten_data" that takes data as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    flatten_recursive with data as data and result as result
    Return result

Process called "flatten_recursive" that takes data as List[Any] and result as List[Any]:
    For each item in data:
        If item is List:
            flatten_recursive with data as item and result as result
        Otherwise:
            Add item to result

Process called "infer_shape" that takes data as List[Any] returns List[Integer]:
    If Collections.List.length with lst as data is equal to 0:
        Return list containing 0
    Let shape be list containing Collections.List.length with lst as data
    If data at index 0 is List:
        Let sub_shape be infer_shape with data as data at index 0
        For each dim in sub_shape:
            Add dim to shape
    Return shape

Process called "calculate_size" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns Integer:
    Let size be 1
    For each dim in shape:
        Set size to size multiplied by dim
    Return size

Process called "calculate_strides" that takes shape as List[Integer] returns List[Integer]:
    Let strides be list containing
    Let current_stride be 1
    For i from Collections.List.length with lst as shape - 1 down to 0:
        Add current_stride to beginning of strides
        Set current_stride to current_stride multiplied by shape at index i
    Return strides

Process called "calculate_flat_index" that takes arr as NDArray and indices as List[Any] returns Integer:
    Let flat_index be 0
    Let num_indices be Math.min with a as Collections.List.length with lst as indices and b as arr.ndim
    For i from 0 to num_indices - 1:
        Let index be Integer.from with value as indices at index i
        Let normalized_index be normalize_index with index as index and size as arr.shape at index i
        Set flat_index to flat_index plus normalized_index multiplied by arr.strides at index i
    Return flat_index

Process called "normalize_index" that takes index as Integer and size as Integer returns Integer:
    If index is less than 0:
        Return Math.max with a as 0 and b as size plus index
    Return Math.min with a as index and b as size - 1

Process called "infer_data_type" that takes data as List[Any] returns DataType:
    If Collections.List.length with lst as data is equal to 0:
        Return Float64
    Let first_item be data at index 0
    If first_item is Integer:
        Return Int64
    If first_item is Float:
        Return Float64
    If first_item is Boolean:
        Return Boolean
    Return Float64

Process called "get_itemsize" that takes dtype as DataType returns Integer:
    Match dtype:
        When Int8 or UInt8 or Boolean:
            Return 1
        When Int16 or UInt16:
            Return 2
        When Int32 or UInt32 or Float32:
            Return 4
        When Int64 or UInt64 or Float64 or Complex64:
            Return 8
        When Complex128:
            Return 16
        Otherwise:
            Return 8

Process called "get_zero_value" that takes dtype as DataType returns Any:
    Match dtype:
        When Boolean:
            Return false
        When Int8 or Int16 or Int32 or Int64 or UInt8 or UInt16 or UInt32 or UInt64:
            Return 0
        When Float32 or Float64:
            Return 0.0
        When Complex64 or Complex128:
            Return dictionary containing "real" and 0.0 and "imaginary" and 0.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0

Process called "get_one_value" that takes dtype as DataType returns Any:
    Match dtype:
        When Boolean:
            Return true
        When Int8 or Int16 or Int32 or Int64 or UInt8 or UInt16 or UInt32 or UInt64:
            Return 1
        When Float32 or Float64:
            Return 1.0
        When Complex64 or Complex128:
            Return dictionary containing "real" and 1.0 and "imaginary" and 0.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 1.0

Process called "create_filled_list" that takes size as Integer and value as Any returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    For i from 0 to size - 1:
        Add value to result
    Return result

Process called "broadcast_arrays" that takes arrays as List[NDArray] returns List[NDArray]:
    Note: Simplified broadcasting - returns arrays as-is for now
    Return arrays

Process called "copy_array" that takes arr as NDArray returns NDArray:
    Return NDArray with:
        data as Collections.List.copy with lst as arr.data
        shape as Collections.List.copy with lst as arr.shape
        strides as Collections.List.copy with lst as arr.strides
        dtype as arr.dtype
        ndim as arr.ndim
        size as arr.size
        itemsize as arr.itemsize
        flags as arr.flags
        metadata as arr.metadata

Note: Type conversion and validation functions
Process called "convert_data_to_type" that takes data as List[Any] and dtype as DataType returns List[Any]:
    Let converted_data be list containing
    For each item in data:
        Add convert_value_to_type with value as item and dtype as dtype to converted_data
    Return converted_data

Process called "convert_value_to_type" that takes value as Any and dtype as DataType returns Any:
    Match dtype:
        When Boolean:
            Return Boolean.from with value as value
        When Int8 or Int16 or Int32 or Int64 or UInt8 or UInt16 or UInt32 or UInt64:
            Return Integer.from with value as value
        When Float32 or Float64:
            Return Float.from with value as value
        When Complex64 or Complex128:
            If value is Dictionary:
                Return value
            Return dictionary containing "real" and Float.from with value as value and "imaginary" and 0.0
        Otherwise:
            Return value

Process called "add_values" that takes a as Any and b as Any and dtype as DataType returns Any:
    Match dtype:
        When Boolean:
            Return Boolean.from with value as a or Boolean.from with value as b
        When Int8 or Int16 or Int32 or Int64 or UInt8 or UInt16 or UInt32 or UInt64:
            Return Integer.from with value as a plus Integer.from with value as b
        When Float32 or Float64:
            Return Float.from with value as a plus Float.from with value as b
        When Complex64 or Complex128:
            Let a_real be if a is Dictionary then a at key "real" else Float.from with value as a
            Let a_imag be if a is Dictionary then a at key "imaginary" else 0.0
            Let b_real be if b is Dictionary then b at key "real" else Float.from with value as b
            Let b_imag be if b is Dictionary then b at key "imaginary" else 0.0
            Return dictionary containing "real" and a_real plus b_real and "imaginary" and a_imag plus b_imag
        Otherwise:
            Return Float.from with value as a plus Float.from with value as b

Process called "multiply_values" that takes a as Any and b as Any and dtype as DataType returns Any:
    Match dtype:
    When Boolean:
    Return Boolean.from with value as a and Boolean.from with value as b
    When Int8 or Int16 or Int32 or Int64 or UInt8 or UInt16 or UInt32 or UInt64:
    Return Integer.from with value as a multiplied by Integer.from with value as b
    When Float32 or Float64:
    Return Float.from with value as a multiplied by Float.from with value as b
    When Complex64 or Complex128:
    Let a_real be if a is Dictionary then a at key "real" else Float.from with value as a
    Let a_imag be if a is Dictionary then a at key "imaginary" else 0.0
    Let b_real be if b is Dictionary then b at key "real" else Float.from with value as b
    Let b_imag be if b is Dictionary then b at key "imaginary" else 0.0
    Let result_real be a_real multiplied by b_real - a_imag multiplied by b_imag
            Let result_imag be a_real multiplied by b_imag plus a_imag multiplied by b_real
            Return dictionary containing "real" and result_real and "imaginary" and result_imag
        Otherwise:
            Return Float.from with value as a multiplied by Float.from with value as b

Note: Advanced utility functions
Process called "check_contiguous" that takes shape as List[Integer] and strides as List[Integer] returns Boolean:
    If Collections.List.length with lst as shape is not equal to Collections.List.length with lst as strides:
        Return false
    Let expected_strides be calculate_strides with shape as shape
    For i from 0 to Collections.List.length with lst as strides - 1:
        If strides at index i is not equal to expected_strides at index i:
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "generate_reverse_axes" that takes ndim as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let axes be list containing
    For i from ndim - 1 down to 0:
        Add i to axes
    Return axes

Process called "create_ones_shape" that takes ndim as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Let shape be list containing
    For i from 0 to ndim - 1:
        Add 1 to shape
    Return shape

Process called "pad_or_truncate_data" that takes data as List[Any] and target_size as Integer returns List[Any]:
    Let current_size be Collections.List.length with lst as data
    If current_size is equal to target_size:
        Return data
    If current_size is less than target_size:
        Let padded_data be Collections.List.copy with lst as data
        Let fill_value be if current_size is greater than 0 then data at index (current_size - 1) else 0.0
        For i from current_size to target_size - 1:
            Add fill_value to padded_data
        Return padded_data
    Return Collections.List.slice with lst as data and start as 0 and end as target_size

Process called "infer_scalar_type" that takes value as Any returns DataType:
    If value is Integer:
        Return Int64
    If value is Float:
        Return Float64
    If value is Boolean:
        Return Boolean
    Return Float64

Note: Placeholder implementations for complex operations
Process called "extract_sliced_data" that takes source as NDArray and target as List[Any] and offset as Integer and shape as List[Integer] and strides as List[Integer]:
    Note: Extract data based on slice specifications
    For i from 0 to calculate_size with shape as shape - 1:
        Add source.data at index (offset plus i) to target

Process called "sum_along_axis" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Integer and keepdims as Boolean returns NDArray:
    Note: Sum along specific axis
    Return copy_array with arr as arr

Process called "max_along_axis" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Integer and keepdims as Boolean returns NDArray:
    Note: Maximum along specific axis
    Return copy_array with arr as arr

Process called "min_along_axis" that takes arr as NDArray and axis as Integer and keepdims as Boolean returns NDArray:
